    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1944-07-17T03:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1944-07-17T03:00:00-05:00" n="1098"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d1098">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">740.00119 Control (Italy)/7–1744: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The American Representative on the Advisory Council for
                        Italy</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Kirk</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Rome</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1944-07-17T10:00:00+02:00"
                            >July 17, 1944—10 a.m.</date>
                        <lb/> [Received 1:57 p.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>15. Under Secretary Foreign Affairs has assured ACC that if reports given in the
                    Department’s 335, July 8, 8 p.m., to me at Naples <pb facs="1192" n="1180"
                        xml:id="pg_1180"/> are true, Swiss Government has acted without knowledge of
                        Bonomi<note n="59" xml:id="d1098fn59">Ivanoe Bonomi succeeded Marshal
                        Badoglio as Italian Prime Minister on June 18, 1944.</note> and Foreign
                    Office. He reiterated that Italian Government fully appreciates ACC is
                    appropriate channel for communication with foreign governments and that there
                    was no intention to depart from this practice.</p>
                <p>Repeated to Algiers as Number 8. Please inform Bern.<note n="60"
                        xml:id="d1098fn60">Telegram 2483, July 21, 1944, not printed. A circular
                        telegram of the same date informed diplomatic representatives in the
                        American Republics of the contents of this telegram.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Kirk</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
